text:
Too fat, too skinny, too muscular, too something... I recently had a family member remark that I was "sooo skinny" (and not in a good way, as if that ever is). As someone who has been skinny, soft, skinny/fat (that's a thing people 🤦), pregnant, lost the baby weight then gained it back, there is nothing more frustrating than having someone criticize your weight. 
My response to this person was that my body was not theirs to observe and have an opinion on. Whether I choose to "let myself go a little" or hit the gym hard, has nothing to do with you. It's a reflection of where I am in my life and the priorities I have. 
It doesn't matter what you look like, someone will always have something to say. Oh and shaping your body to please everyone is absolutely impossible. I am the fittest I have ever been and someone's interpretation of that is that I'm too skinny. Others will say I'm too muscular and to lighten up on those weights before I look too masculine (yes I have also gotten that feedback). My diet is far from perfect. My gym routine is not always consistent. And I like wine🍷. If you like how I look, cool. If not, look past. I'm on a mission of becoming the best version of myself in all areas of my life and those who try to slow me down will get left behind. 
Do you. 😘💪❤️
Cá hú thì muôn đời vẫn là cá hú. Chẳng khá lên chút nào 🏋️‍♀️🏋️‍♀️🏋️‍♀️

text:
Negative comments about one's appearance can come from anyone, including well-meaning family members.
Academic studies and research indicate that we live in an image-heavy society online and in person. We see the promotion of an 'ideal body' in advertisements, magazines, newspapers, billboards, shopping windows, etc. 
Weight stigma which is a negative response to someone based on their weight, is the fourth most common form of social discrimination amongst adults. It is the only form of discrimination which is still widely deemed to be socially acceptable.
We claim ourselves to be a modern and progressive society, yet we continue to judge and discriminate. 
Body shaming has a direct impact on the mental health of people, and makes them dissatisfied and unhappy.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
I really wanted to post this picture and share something that always conflicts me from within about our time.....
This is me, 6 years ago.... I had just joined my engineering college and was a part of a metal band as a drummer and for a really long time...i wished to grow my hair long and when i reached in college, i chose to grow them then..... it took me almost 2 years to grow them to the longest they were(unfortunately I don’t have a picture of that day). I took immense care of them, researched, applied products to make them the way i wanted my hair to be..and when they did grow, i was very happy!
Now when i talk about the society in general and the society in which i enlist myself (coz everyone is part of a society), some loved my hair and some thought i was foolish to do what i did not just my hair but to “myself” and let me be clear these were and are some of the closest people around me and i still love and will always do....but to be honest this was a straight forward case of body shaming (please don’t take this in the wrong way). But i never felt bad about being subjected to such criticism for what i chose to do. And recently I realised the reason for that coz i just decided to grow them back again and i once again heard a lot of opinion. The reason was “me and my awareness which taught me not only to believe in what i believe, but also to differentiate between a comment which  is just a comment and a statement made deliberately to body shame me”, and i would like to share the same with everyone!! “The first person who needs to be comfortable and accept what they are or what they wanna be is the first hand concerned individual itself!! PERIOD!!” And after that you not only see the statements turning into compliments but also the inner belief and the growth of self respect one starts to feel for themselves....
SO PEOPLE!! JUST OWN IT!! If you’re hairy and wanna be clean shaved, OWN IT!! If you’re “FAT” and you love being “FAT”, OWN IT!! Love yourself..♥️

text:
I don’t even have words for how I feel right now. Veezy is six and occasionally asks to play games on the iPad. The website we allow is the one his kindergarten uses for fun learning games during informatics. He was sitting next to me when I glanced over and saw this nonsense. My six year old was “making a girl pretty” by removing her freckles/skin blemishes, adding eye lashes... and then broke out a SCALPEL to fix her nose. What in the ever loving god was that?!? I grabbed the iPad the moment the scalpel came out. Turns out an ad banner with other games appeared on the page (I’m seriously hoping the school has firewalls preventing these), and my kid innocently clicked on what just looked like more games. Seriously, though, this is where it starts. Who is making and marketing these games to preschoolers?!? Not only are kids bombarded with this stuff on tv, etc, games are being pushed where “imperfections” are fixed with scalpels. I’m glad we were watching, but this is just another reminder to pay attention and talk to children about beauty - it comes in all shapes, sizes, colours, and more. Work with your kids to actively oppose body shaming. ALL bodies are worthy of love and kindness.
.
.
 bodypositive @bodyposipanda @jameelajamilofficial @bodyimage_therapist

text:
I've always been thin. I'd never experienced being fat. Yet, I know how being fat feels like. Because the society we live in now is full of judgmental people. 
I've been called 'teeli', 'chipkali', 'lakri', 'hadiyon ka dhaancha', 'sukhi chiri' and much more I can't remember rn. And it hurts... It really DOES! .
My sister/friend who's a lil' fat has been called 'bhens', 'moti', and blah blah (sometimes by my ownself). And ik she must feel bad when people(including me) call her with those names! .
I think fat people can be encouraged to do exercise or join gym or else just walk after meals. Thus, they can make themselves smart and healthy in some ways. 
But us, thin people, we can't do anything. I sometimes eat a lot. Not at home but at school. But its just that ke wo khana kahin lagta nahi hai! Its not our fault. Its how our bodies work. .
Just stop making us feel bad about ourselves. Please! STOP THIS BODY SHAMING. Specially these khaandaan ki aunties whom we are not even free with (Ik they can't read this post), they make us/me feel worse. Idk why but still. These aunties need to stop. The people whom we interact with after a whole year and they comeup with, 'Ohhh... Aik saal me kitni moti/patli ho gai ho.',they need to stop. .

text:
On  bodyshaming

I suffered deep emotional hurts from people calling me out on my scanty (light) hair. This had a huge negative impact on my self-esteem. I remember there was a time I couldn't leave my house wearing just my hair (as a secondary school student). If it wasn't threaded or braided with attachment, I would tie a bandana to cover it. .
.
The shame and helplessness I felt then in my life was something else.
.
.
I love my hair today - still scanty, but hey, I'm not perfect, and frankly, I don't need to be (God made my hair this way).
.
.
Note to adults (parents, aunts/uncles, big sis/bro, teachers etc.): Do not tease a child with their physical challenges ("playfully", "jokingly" or otherwise). You are damaging his/her self-esteem each time you do. You're basically saying to the child: "you are not good enough". Because the mind is highly impressionable (esp. that of kids), the child will believe you. Stop raising timid children. Stop body shaming ANYONE.
.
.
Have you been body-shamed before? How did that make you feel? .
.
.
.

text:
Jede Falte erzählt eine Geschichte über mich und mein Leben.... Mein ganzer Körper erzählt eine Geschichte.

Leider wollen wir diese Geschichten, die Vergangenheit oft einfach ausradieren, wegretuschieren, so tun als ob es das alles nie gegeben hätte... Mein Körper ist nicht einfach nur ein Körper, der nicht der „Norm“ entspricht, dem was mir auf jedem Kanal, in den Medien, im Umfeld als „annehmbar“ suggeriert wird. 
Mein Körper ist ein Wunderwerk. Wenn ich mich mit der Anatomie beschäftige, mit dem was da alles, ohne dass ich es bewusst merke, abläuft, dann kann ich eigentlich nur staunen.

Dieser Körper trägt mich schon Jahrzehnte durchs Leben.

Wir sind alle so verschieden, weil wir unterschiedliche Geschichten haben. 
Schade, wenn wir uns gegenseitig immer nur die gleiche Geschichte erzählen wollen, oder?

 fühlen

text: It’d been calculated that if Barbie were human sized she would stand about six feet tall with a 39" bust, 18" waist, and 33" hips. Though unusual for sure, and unattainable for many women, these measurements are certainly within the realm of possibility for the human body. Contrast that He-Man, who would also stand approximately six feet tall (though some estimates put him as tall as 6’4”) have a 71” chest, 29” calves, and weigh over 700lbs. All of which is humanly impossible to accomplish.

text:
People will make fun of you if you’re fat. They’ll make fun of you if you’re skinny. They’ll roll their eyes when you’re fit. People will be annoyed when you’re happy, and tell you to “cheer up” when you’re depressed. 🤷🏼‍♀️
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Lucky for me I’ve gotten to experience the negativity from others! Yes you read that right! 🍀 By putting my fitness journey out there every day I get nasty comments once in a while, it’s part of social media unfortunately 🤷🏼‍♀️ Everyone talks tough through a screen, I just smile and shrug because I know they’d never say it to my face and CLEARLY they are unhappy with themselves if they take time out of their day to try to put me down 🙃
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
You can’t please everyone okay? So keep doing the things that make you happy! Don’t stop taking care of yourself because someone thinks it’s “extra” ... like what? Since when is taking care of yourself too much? 😂 Keep doing what you’re doing girl and drink some water 🤗

thinprivilege and  fatphobia IS REAL. All  bodyshaming needs to end.
.

Repeated commenting after the fact will lead to the user being blocked for violating the safety of the community/not contributing to discussions by harassing others.* ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
[ID: Tumblr post that reads: “what are your thoughts on ‘skinny shaming’?”
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Reblog reads: “As someone who has been “thin-shamed” I can say it does Not at all go hand in hand with fat shaming. People “thin-shaming” me was mostly verbal harassment- you’re too skinny, you look like a boy, eat a fucking cheeseburger, what’s wrong with you why don’t you like food?
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
But guess what, I don’t have a problem finding clothes that fit me. There aren’t companies that refuse to make clothes for my size. There is no shortage of messages telling me that despite the harassment of some, I am still beautiful and ideal even if I’m unhealthy. Despite being thin-shamed, I still PANICKED when I started a medicine that made me gain weight, and I had to really analyze that, because no matter what my culture will still say that “fat is unideal” “fat is bad” and “honestly its fine to starve yourself / but shameful and bad to overeat.” ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
So “thin-shaming” is shitty because it’s shitty to be judged and have people make assumptions about you. But Fat-shaming is institutional, it’s not just individuals harassment and judgement, it’s potential jobs, it’s clothing companies, it’s media and advertisement, all telling you you’re bad as you are. Like what a way shittier thing.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Reblog 2 reads: “this is the difference.”] [tags:

text:
The mom who is thin. Can we talk about thin privilege? What is it? From what I’ve researched and listened to from other bloggers it is essentially the luxury of not having to deal with fat shaming. There is so much that goes a long with that of course. Basically I don’t have people groan or roll their eyes when they sit next to me on a plane, I can shop at any store I’d like, I don’t get ugly looks when I eat a pizza, my bathing suit choice isn’t judged at the pool, and I would probably go as far as saying I get better customer service because of my size as well. All of that is a privilege because of my size. I could be the biggest jerk, and still all of the above applies. If you think this isn’t a thing look around next time you’re at the store, on the subway, in a line at McDonald’s. Open your eyes and truly look at your sisters all around you. I can sit here and tell a size 12+ woman she’s gorgeous all day, but my opinion comes with an emptiness and a lack of empathy. I want to be on the right side of this body positive movement that I’ve been following through accounts such as @thegarciadiaries and @thebirdspapaya and I want to genuinely spread love and acceptance but I am a mom who is thin, and while I still struggle with every roll or stretch mark I have, I realize that my body is what society deems acceptable. There was a time when curves and a little junk in the trunk is what was sold as Sexy. Marilyn Monroe is proof of that. What happened? When did it change? How can I as a thin women, use my influence in this movement without coming across as naive? @mingey recently said “INFLUENCE = POWER. And if you’re taking advantage of that- EMPOWER.” .
.
.
.

text:
Hvordan har du det med din krop?

Er den blød, fast, slap, stærk, tynd, tyk, bred, smal, høj, lav, bulet, arret, osv.? Jeg er nysgerrig efter at vide, hvorfor du tænker om din krop som du gør? Uanset hvad du tænker! 
Jeg vil gerne starte med at dele lidt fra mit eget liv, som har påvirket mig en stor del af livet; 
Som barn tænkte jeg aldrig over min krop. Jeg var bare. 
Jeg husker, at jeg synes, at min hud var dejlig blød, at mine fregner var sjove og flotte. Det var altid sjovt at holde øje med dem om foråret, når forårssolen gjorde dem ekstra tydelige. 
Min krop var et rart sted at være og den var god til at løbe hurtigt, klatre og så var den smidig. 
Jeg var ikke særlig gammel, da jeg kom i puberteten, min krop ændrede sig, jeg fik former som den første i klassen, og jeg stod for skud i forhold til bemærkninger og kommentarer. 
Særligt én bemærkning, der en dag blev slynget ud i klasseværelset,  bed sig fast; “Anja, har sgu da en kæmpe røv!”
Af en eller anden årsag røg den ikke ind ad det ene øre og ud ad det andet? 
En kæmpe røv! Bum! Det var, hvad jeg havde!
Det sjove var, at min numse ikke var kæmpe, men at jeg troede på det?
Jeg troede på det og dem der sagde det modsatte, troede jeg ikke på? De var sikkert bare høflige. 
Det skal lige siges, at jeg ikke var ked af min numse - den var bare stor! Jeg blev ked af at blive vurderet!
Senere - efter jeg blev mor - mødte jeg en fyr der en dag, da vi lavede mad, pegede på min mave og sagde; “hvad er det?” Jeg kiggede ned, fordi jeg troede, at jeg havde spildt. “Hvad mener du?”, spurgte jeg. 
Han gentog sit spørgsmål uden jeg fattede noget som helst, hvorefter han sagde; “Er du ikke lidt tyk?” Fra den dag begyndte jeg, at se på mig selv med andre(s) øjne. 
Jeg begyndte at kritisere min krop. 
Den var for tyk, for bred og jeg kom i tanke om, at nogle engang havde sagt, at mine tær var underlige og jo mere jeg kiggede, jo mere gav jeg dem ret. 
Jeg blev utrolig opmærksom på, hvordan andre så ud, hvilket tøj de gik i og jeg sammenlignede mig med dem. 
Det var lidt af min historie - kender du det fra dig selv eller har du en anden historie? 
FORTSÆTTER 👇🏽
comment_1:

ALLE ER PERFEKTE, NÅR VI STOPPER MED AT SAMMENLIGNE!

Kig dig lige i spejlet skønne du og se hvor vidunderlig din krop er!

Har du brug for at blive bedre til at se hvor unik dig er, er du velkommen til at kontakte mig til en uforpligtende snak, så vi finder ud af om jeg er den rette til at hjælpe dig. 
Anja ❤️

text:
TOPIC  38; Wimbledon Fashion, Seating, Appearance, ETC. 
Straight to it, shall we? 
1. WHY IS PIPPA ALSO IN THE ROYAL BOX? 
According to the official Wimbledon website, the Royal Box is used for friends and guests of Wimbledon, which includes "British and overseas royal families, heads of government, people from the world of tennis, commercial partners, British Armed Forces, prominent media organisations, supporters of tennis and other walks of life". This means that IF the GUESTS of Wimbledon have in turned invited you to come along, like Pippa has YEARS ago, they are allowed to turn out. If not, it would have to be by invitation of the President of Wimbledon. 
2. KATES APPEARANCE - Kate's dress was last worn in 2016, this is a repeat. I'm not sure WHAT the issue is with the fit, and WHAT the issue IS with wearing clothes that have similar fit and flare, or patterns or Colours. It's not you who is wearing the dress. 
Here are some PSYCHOLOGICAL REASONS behind why women sometimes gravitate towards a certain style OR "work uniforms". - we instinctively gravitate towards the clothes that originally made us feel great, safe and secure. Especially in this harsh world of a royal, where EVERYONE is thinking their opinions are the ONLY correct one, it is hard not to be affected. As such, we tend to hold on to the things that remind us of happier times of which could manifest in our fashion choices. - People tend to wear things that they LIKE and have found to suit their body shape. As with all happy memories, the endorphins that come with finding something that SUITS YOUR body shape and YOU, tends to stick with you. The comfort and confidence that comes with often leads people to buying things in a certain way. - Kate seems to be the "classic fashion type". This means A) Investment in clothing to be reworn over YEARS, B) sticking to classic lines, things that suit her, C) Basically, the clothes have proven to be a HIT. So that means less criticisms, more focus on her patronages, as well as acting as a "work uniform". Frankly, it's easier to stick to something than try something new all the time. There's no pressure to change her fashion choices, very frankly

text:
Dear Body, 
I am sorry for not treating you the way you should be treated. I apologize for accepting all the comments on you thrown by the society. When the society was screaming, 'Skinny' constantly, I believed it. I am sorry that I accepted so many lies about you. I want you to know it wasn't me who hated you but the society constantly pressurizing me to hate you and fit into something called 'Perfect'
You've been a home to my soul for the past 24 years and I'm grateful for all that you've done so far. I love you for being so Flawless. 
I promise you, I'll not let other people's opinions upset me because at the end it's my opinion that counts. You are my business and nobody's else. You are my body. I will care for you and provide you with all the nourishment that you need. You are a tiny universe and I am not going to fit you into the mold of unattainable acceptability defined by the society. 
You are a recovering warrior. I will trust you and treasure you🖤
.

text:
Ach mensch das Gewicht ist bei vielen ein ewiges Thema 🙄 Momentan habe ich übergewicht und bin am abnehmen, für mich ist das Gewicht nicht wichtig sondern das ich mich wohlfühle wenn ich in den Spiegel sehe🥰 Ich habe durch mein eigenes „Programm“ das für mich funktioniert 💕letztes Jahr schon knappe 12 Kilo abgenommen😸 und trotz meines momentanen Gewichts wünsche ich mir jetzt ein Baby, ich weis das ich nach der 2ten SS noch mehr auf den Rippen habe😂 aber Leute ganz ehrlich....... auch das kriege ich wieder runter💪🏼🔥 denn ich bin heute schon sportlich und habe meine Ernährung umgestellt aber ich lasse mir Zeit⏱ denn mir ist wichtig alles dann auch unten zu halten und nicht gleich wieder zu zunehmen♥️☺️ Ich bin ehrlich gesagt kein Fan von Abnehmtees oder Kaffes oder Shakes oder was auch immer✌🏼☺️....... Ich esse einfach vernünftig und nicht zwischendurch, ich gehe nicht ins Fitnesstudio sondern bewege mich wann immer ich kann und mache ab und zu ein Workout Zuhause (man kann FAST alles Zuhause oder Draussen nachmachen ohne gross Geld auszugeben) aber natürlich darf das jeder so halten wie er es gut findet🥰 Aber es ist schade das uns Mamas schon fast aufgezwungen wird das „perfekte Aussehen“ oder das „perfekte Gewicht“ nach der Schwangerschaft zu haben🧐 Warum eigentlich? Man muss sich in seinem Körper wohlühlen und das geht nur wenn DU so lebst und bist wie es dir gefällt😘💋 Ein falsch gibt es nicht, denn wir Menschen sind alle individuell und das bedeutet jeder ist eigen, mit seinenen Ecken und Kanten💕 Lebe wie du leben willst und sei so wie du dich wohlfühlst🍀❤️
